INSERT INTO `drupal_node_revisions` VALUES ('8','8','1','Kaslo History','<p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"intro\">The citizens of this small village show a resourcefulness as great as the mountains, rivers and lakes that are features of the landscape in which they live. In 1889 and 1890 G.O. Buchanan and brothers George and David Kane came to Kaslo to stake timber claims. When silver mining activity was reported in the area, the Kane brothers subdivided their lease into town lots.</p><p>The population soon grew to 3,000 people, most of them intent on seeking their fortunes in the newly discovered mines.</p><p>Disaster struck in 1894 as fire, flood and gale force winds came in succession. In February, half of the town\'s commercial district was destroyed, as well as 60-70 houses, two hotels, the jail and several other two storey buildings.</p><p>By 1895 and \'96, Kaslo had turned her fortunes around with the completion of the K&amp;S Railway, a public telephone system, and electric and waterworks plants. By 1897 Kaslo had all the services of a progressive mining supply centre: a cigar factory, brewery, dry goods stores, several saloons, hotels and brothels and its own newspaper-The Kootenaian.</p><p>Over the next 50 years, metal prices fell and mining costs rose, resulting in a decline in mining activity and in the viability of the town. For a while fruit-ranching was a thriving industry until the Little Cherry disease destroyed the marketability of the fruit. But the villagers never gave up. Eventually a home-grown economy was created that was varied enough to withstand the changes of time. Lifestyle, tourism, small and home based businesses are now the foundation of Kaslo\'s prosperity.</p><p><img alt=\"Pioneers in front of a log cabin.\" class=\"clear-all-center\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: thin; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; display: block; padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-left-color: black; border-left-style: initial; float: center; padding-right: 10px; padding-left: 10px; clear: both; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; \" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/history1.jpg\" /></p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \">Front Street: What\'s Old is New Again</p><p class=\"intro\">Over the last 25 years, merchants along Kaslo\'s main street have stripped away the &quot;modern&quot; cladding and have painstakingly restored the highly decorative and characteristically western facades of the original storefronts. A different story has played out for the Kaslo Hotel  its new owners have effected the re-birth of an idea.</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \">&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"front_st\" width=\"334\" height=\"126\" class=\"float-right\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: thin; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; display: block; padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-left-color: black; border-left-style: initial; float: right; padding-right: 10px; padding-left: 10px; \" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/front_st.jpg\" /></p><p>The original Kaslo Hotel, built on the same location in 1896, was very grand and fine for its time. In the early 20th century, it was the heart of a bustling and optimistic community. But the promise represented by its lavish detail and stately interior spaces waned along with the fortunes of the townspeople and it fell into disrepair, finally closing in the 1920s. The building was then acquired by the village for non-payment of taxes. From 1942 to 1945 it was used as housing for Japanese-Canadian internees. In 1950 it burned and was razed to the ground.</p><p>A new Kaslo Hotel was constructed and it opened in 1958 on the original site. It operated continuously, although its name was changed to the Mariner Inn in 1981. In 2006 the Mariner was sold. The present building, renamed The Kaslo Hotel, has been completely transformed so that, once again, an elegant establishment graces the top of Front Street.</p><div>&nbsp;</div><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','<p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"intro\">The citizens of this small village show a resourcefulness as great as the mountains, rivers and lakes that are features of the landscape in which they live. In 1889 and 1890 G.O. Buchanan and brothers George and David Kane came to Kaslo to stake timber claims. When silver mining activity was reported in the area, the Kane brothers subdivided their lease into town lots.</p><p>The population soon grew to 3,000 people, most of them intent on seeking their fortunes in the newly discovered mines.</p>','','1258159825','2');
INSERT INTO `drupal_node_revisions` VALUES ('9','9','1','Arts and Culture','<div><div id=\"indexheader\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;\"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"102\" alt=\"The History of the People of Kaslo\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/a&amp;e.gif\" /></div></div>  <div id=\"content\" style=\"clear: both; display: block; top: 50px; left: 0px; width: 500px; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 14px; line-height: 15px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;\"><p class=\"intro\">This is an area filled with creative people who are inspired by our beautiful surroundings of lakes and mountains. From pottery to painting, sculptures to quilts, there is much to choose from. If you are looking for the perfect handmade gift for yourself or friends, you will not be disappointed.</p><p>Explore the studios, galleries and shops of the artists and artisans mentioned here.</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\">Linda Cole -The Last Stitch</span><br />There is always something new on the quilting frame at The Last Stitch Quilt Shoppe. Visit expert longarm quilter Linda Cole, at her working studio on Front Street.</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\"><img width=\"180\" height=\"220\" alt=\"Fern\'s-truck\" class=\"float-right\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; padding: 10px; display: block; border-left-color: black; float: right;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/Fern\'s-truck.jpg\" />Fern Van Horn - Fern\'s</span><br />Native to BC, Fern Van Horn has been drawing and painting her whole life. Working primarily in water colours or acrylic, her subjects are usually those with a &quot;past&quot;; old trucks, old toys or gnarly old trees.</p><p>Light and colour characterize Fern\'s work and charge it with a sense of excitement and energy. &quot;I am inspired to give my subjects one more chance at centre stage.&quot; Her work is displayed in various galleries and at Fern\'s.</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\">Jeremy Behn</span><br />Trained by master luthiers Michael Dunn and Ray Nurse, Jeremy has been building and repairing instruments for 15 years. A recipient of a Canada Council grant and BC Arts Council grant, he now divides his time between playing music, building and repairing instruments and most recently, carving. See ad page 6 (Instruments of Change)</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\"><img width=\"200\" height=\"160\" alt=\"Circle1-by-Carole\" class=\"float-right\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; padding: 10px; display: block; border-left-color: black; float: right;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/Circle1-by-Carole.jpg\" />Carole Danyluk</span><br />has been involved in the art world for her entire life. It was during her years at the University of Calgary that she was first exposed to bronze casting as an art form.</p>Carole and husband Rick Taylor reside in Kaslo where they own and operate the White Goat Gallery of Wildlife Art, which offers an extensive selection of bronze sculptures by these artists.<p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\">Rick Taylor</span>&nbsp;<br />is one of the most renowned wildlife artists on the contemporary sculpture scene. His art is appreciated and collected by museums and individuals from all over the world.</p><p>His focus is centered on wild sheep but his artwork covers species and subjects from all corners of the globe.</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\"><img width=\"73\" height=\"110\" alt=\"Figments-Alfoldy-print\" class=\"float-right\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; padding: 10px; display: block; border-left-color: black; float: right;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/Figments-Alfoldy-print.jpg\" />Figments</span><br />Since 1986, Figments has been selling a unique collection of hand-crafted products from across Canada and around the world. Customers will find creations in a broad variety of media - glass, pottery, metal, fabric, and paper products-with a focus on Canadian products but also including fairly-traded products from select international artisans.<span style=\"font-size: larger;\"><br /></span></p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\"><img width=\"200\" height=\"146\" alt=\"Bowl-&amp;-Spurtle\" class=\"float-right\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; padding: 10px; display: block; border-left-color: black; float: right;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/Bowl-&amp;-Spurtle.jpg\" />David Stewart</span><br />divides his time between making things out of wood and making music. He spends as much time as possible in his Argenta workshop specializing in turned wood products - everything from spurtles to large salad bowls.</p><p>Most of his products have a practical use, but he gently pushes the limits of his craft, with eccentric turnings and ebonized wood, resulting in some unique pieces.</p><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both;\">Gallery-Bluebelle Bistro &amp; Beanery&nbsp;<br />Be sure to check out the ongoing display of local artwork on the walls and in the windows of the Bluebelle Bistro &amp; Beanery, such as the work of Anne Gray.</p><br /><p>&nbsp;</p></div></div>','<div><div id=\"indexheader\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;\"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"102\" alt=\"The History of the People of Kaslo\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/a&amp;e.gif\" /></div></div>  <div id=\"content\" style=\"clear: both; display: block; top: 50px; left: 0px; width: 500px; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style','','1262737854','2');
INSERT INTO `drupal_node_revisions` VALUES ('10','10','1','Environment','<div style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; -x-system-font: none;\" id=\"indexheader\"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"102\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/environment.gif\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" alt=\"The Forest &amp; the Trees\" /></div></div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"clear: both; display: block; top: 50px; left: 0px; width: 500px; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 14px; line-height: 15px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; -x-system-font: none;\" id=\"content\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p class=\"intro\">If you were to fly over the village of Kaslo, you\'d be struck by how small this community is in the surrounding vastness of the forested hills and mountains that seem to go on forever.</p><p>Take a walk through these forests and you\'ll begin to see the trees. There is huge diversity here  it\'s known as the Kootenay mix. Fir, larch, cedar, hemlock and pine tower above you. A rich variety of species of trees, plants, animals and birds all thrive in this area  the second wettest climate zone in the province after the coastal rainforest.</p></td></tr><tr><td><div align=\"center\"><img width=\"490\" height=\"270\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/environment1.jpg\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; display: block; padding-top: 4px; padding-bottom: 8px; border-left-color: black;\" alt=\"Mountains &amp; Trees.\" /></div></td></tr><tr><td><p>Elevation, as you might expect in this mountainous area, is a major defining factor for what can flourish in a particular ecosystem, or biogeoclimatic zone. But so is the degree of slope and the aspect  how much sunshine? how steep? how high?</p><p>Wildfires from lightning strikes have always altered the forested hills. Only the cedars in the wet valley bottoms and the Douglas fir with its thick bark have a measure of protection against the sporadic seasonal fires. Look across the lake at the mountain slopes and see the forest fire history. If you can spy a subtle patterning of patches, rather like a sculpted wool carpet, you\'re seeing the varied ages of stands and the extent of old fires.</p><p>Most of the forest you see here is &quot;Crown land&quot;. The forest is an asset of the province of British Columbia. Local companies big and small &quot;work in the bush&quot; and many Kaslo and area families have for generations gained their livelihood because of this great resource. Kaslo and area also holds the tenure to a small part of the forestlands nearby. The Kaslo and District Community Forest Society has a licence for the rights and responsibilities associated with an annual harvest of 25,000 cubic metres of timber within its designated chart area.</p></td></tr><tr><td><div align=\"center\"><img width=\"490\" height=\"262\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/environment2.jpg\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; display: block; padding-top: 4px; padding-bottom: 8px; border-left-color: black;\" alt=\"River &amp; Trees.\" /></div></td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','<div style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; -x-system-font: none;\" id=\"indexheader\"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"102\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/environment.gif\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" alt=\"The Forest &amp; the Trees\" /></div></div>\r\n\r','','1262737927','2');
INSERT INTO `drupal_node_revisions` VALUES ('11','11','1','Events','<div><div id=\"indexheader\" align=\"center\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font: normal normal bolder 24px/26px \'Lucida Grand\', Arial, sans-serif; \"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"102\" alt=\"The History of the People of Kaslo\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; display: block; \" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/events.gif\" /></div></div>    <strong>Music in the Bay</strong><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \">It\'ll be another unforgettable weekend at this year\'s Kaslo Jazz Etc Festival. Bands are making their way from around the world to play in the outdoor natural amphitheatre of Kaslo Bay Park. This festival fills the air with music every year on the August long weekend: this year July 31 through August 2. USA Today rated this festival as one of the top 10 in North America.</p><p>Mountains rising over 10,000 feet from the lake are the backdrop for the performers. Musicians entertain from a floating stage in the bay. The audience can watch and listen while reclining on the sandy beach, or even while swimming in the water around the stage.</p><p>Friday July 31, there will be free concerts in downtown Kaslo featuring the Aaron Nazrul Band and Mimosa. Kaslo Friday Night Country Etc Concert in the bay will feature Blackie &amp; The Rodeo Kings, The festival program continues on Saturday and Sunday with a lineup of great jazz and bluesinfl uenced artists: Richie Havens, Bill Evans/Soulgrass, Elmer Ferrer Band, Five Alarm Funk to mention a few.</p><p>Food and craft vendors are on site at the park. You are welcome to bring your own picnic but no glass bottles will be allowed. Festival organizers are striving for a goal of zero waste, so vendors will be using all compostable plates and cups and recycling bins will be available. Check out&nbsp;<a style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); \" href=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/www.kaslojazzfest.com\">kaslojazzfest.com</a>&nbsp;for the schedule, ticket prices and information about the performers.</p><img width=\"490\" height=\"260\" alt=\"Kaslo Jazz Fest.\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: thin; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; display: block; padding-top: 4px; padding-bottom: 8px; border-left-color: black; border-left-style: initial; float: center; \" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/events1.jpg\" /><hr style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; height: 1px; width: 400px; background-image: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; -webkit-background-clip: initial; -webkit-background-origin: initial; background-color: rgb(191, 178, 48); background-position: initial initial; \" /><a id=\"2\" name=\"2\" style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); \"></a><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \"><strong>May Days - May 16 - 18, 2009<br /></strong>This celebration is over 100 years old. From the days of the silver boom to today, it is a quaint festival celebrating Queen Victoria\'s birthday. The May Pole dance has been performed by the young for almost as many years. If you have lived in Kaslo long enough, you or your family members have danced this ancient dance. The weekend begins with the choosing of the May Queen on Friday. Saturday and Sunday are filled with logger sport competitions, ball games, carnival games, car show and craft faire. On Monday watch the parade and relax to music in the park. It is a festival not to be missed.</p><img width=\"490\" height=\"249\" alt=\"Kaslo May Days.\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: thin; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; display: block; padding-top: 4px; padding-bottom: 8px; border-left-color: black; border-left-style: initial; float: center; \" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/events2.jpg\" /><hr style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; height: 1px; width: 400px; background-image: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; -webkit-background-clip: initial; -webkit-background-origin: initial; background-color: rgb(191, 178, 48); background-position: initial initial; \" /><a id=\"3\" name=\"3\" style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); \"></a><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \"><strong>Winter in the Forest<br /></strong>Celebrate winter with sleigh rides, snowshoe races, interpretive nature booths, and maple taffy on the snow. The villagers come out for a day of fun and adventure. This festival is sponsored by the Community Forest and is a great family event.</p><hr style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; height: 1px; width: 400px; background-image: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; -webkit-background-clip: initial; -webkit-background-origin: initial; background-color: rgb(191, 178, 48); background-position: initial initial; \" /><a id=\"4\" name=\"4\" style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); \"></a><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \"><strong>Twisted Tuesdays<br /></strong>Fun in February could be the other title for this crazy event. Employees of the local paper, Pennywise, began it as a winter diversion. Now everyone gets dressed up for Tuesday\'s themes: outlandish hair or hat, pajamas, mardi gras, tropical and favourite character to mention a few. Money raised goes to the hospital, library and other causes. There is no place on earth where you can have as much fun on Tuesdays in February.</p><hr style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; height: 1px; width: 400px; background-image: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; -webkit-background-clip: initial; -webkit-background-origin: initial; background-color: rgb(191, 178, 48); background-position: initial initial; \" /><a id=\"5\" name=\"5\" style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); \"></a><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \"><strong>A stroll for the senses<br /></strong>10 From the spoken word to live music, visual arts and dance, Artwalk brings it all to downtown Kaslo. Featuring local artists and artisans, Artwalk is a fine representation of what the Kootenays has to offer. Artwalk runs from June 19 to September 12 and maps are available at the Langham, Visitor\'s Centre and at participating businesses around town.</p><p>Opening night celebration is on&nbsp;<b>Friday, June 19 and starts at 5 pm</b>. The streets will be alive with people following the self-guided tour and performers enticing them along with their music and performances. Then at 6:30 pm - 7:30 pm enjoy&nbsp;<b>Wine &amp; Cheese</b>&nbsp;at the Langham and more live performances.</p><p>Other places where local art can be viewed include:<br />Treehouse Restaurant, The Langham Cultural Centre, and Kootenay Lake Gallery</p><hr style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; height: 1px; width: 400px; background-image: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; -webkit-background-clip: initial; -webkit-background-origin: initial; background-color: rgb(191, 178, 48); background-position: initial initial; \" /><a id=\"6\" name=\"6\" style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); \"></a><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \"><strong>The Langham<br /></strong>The Langham Hotel was built in 1896 during the heyday of mining. It was so busy during this economic high that beds were rented in three shifts a day. The bar ran from the front of the building right to the back and never stopped serving up drinks. As years passed, it saw many other incarnations: a bottling plant; a wooden boat factory and a bank. During the Second World War the Langham was used as an internment centre for approximately 80 Canadians of Japanese descent. As time went on, it fell into disrepair, and there was a movement to tear down the building. In the 1970s a group of energetic young people believed it could be restored and become the local cultural centre. After much hard work and fundraising activities, they succeeded, and a new era began for the Langham.</p><p>Today, the Langham houses galleries, studios and offices, an intimate and well-used theatre that can accommodate 75 people, and the Japanese Canadian Museum. During the year the public can view a variety of art shows in the galleries or participate in workshops covering a wide spectrum of disciplines. This summer, the Artists In Action series at the Langham offers the opportunity for artists to work on their own projects under the mentorship of professional visual and literary artists.</p><p>The Japanese Canadian Museum experience begins with a series of photographs and writings hung on the walls of the stairwell and 2nd floor hall. This heritage hotel housed 80 internees during World War ll. On the third floor you can view a re-creation of the quarters of a family of Nisei (Canadian citizens of Japanese descent) and find out what it must have been like to live in internal exile in one\'s own country. The Japanese Canadian Museum was opened on May 23, 1993 and dedicated to the Japanese Canadians, their courage under adversity and their ability to overcome injustice.<img width=\"490\" height=\"405\" alt=\"Kaslo\'s Langham: Repository for art &amp; culture.\" class=\"clear-all-center\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: thin; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; display: block; padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-left-color: black; border-left-style: initial; float: center; padding-right: 10px; padding-left: 10px; clear: both; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; \" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/a&amp;e1.jpg\" /></p><p>Langham Gallery hours are Thursday through Sunday, 1 - 4 pm. The Japanese Canadian museum is open daily from 9 am - 4 pm. For more information call 250-353- 2661, or email langham@netidea.com, or you can go to their website&nbsp;<a style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); \" href=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/www.thelangham.ca\">www.thelangham.ca</a></p></div>','<div><div id=\"indexheader\" align=\"center\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font: normal normal bolder 24px/26px \'Lucida Grand\', Arial, sans-serif; \"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"102\" alt=\"The History of the People of Kaslo\" style=\"border-top-width: 0px; border-right-width: 0px; border-bottom-width: 0px; border-left-width: 0px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; display: block; \" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/events.gif\" /></div></div>    <strong>Music in the Bay</strong><p class=\"header\" style=\"clear: both; \">It\'ll be another unforgettable weekend at this ye','','1258160065','2');
INSERT INTO `drupal_node_revisions` VALUES ('12','12','1','S.S. Moyie','<div>\r\n<div align=\"center\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; -x-system-font: none;\" id=\"indexheader\">\r\n\r\n<div align=\"center\">\r\n<img height=\"99\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/moyie.gif\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" alt=\"The History of the People of Kaslo\" />\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"clear: both; display: block; top: 50px; left: 0px; width: 500px; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 14px; line-height: 15px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; -x-system-font: none;\" id=\"content\">\r\n\r\n<p style=\"clear: both;\" class=\"header\">\r\n<strong>The SS Moyie is one of Kaslo\'s gems.<br /></strong>\r\nShe holds within her hull the history of an entire region and the stories of its settlement. It has been 50 years since the SS Moyie, the oldest intact passenger sternwheeler in the world, made her last sailing on Kootenay Lake. Today the ship is dry-docked and open to the public. Spend a morning touring its interior and see elegant Victorian decor, historic artifacts, and realistic displays.\r\n\r\n<img width=\"300\" height=\"201\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/moyie-at-wharf.jpg\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; padding: 10px; display: block; border-left-color: black; float: right;\" class=\"float-right\" alt=\"moyie-at-wharf\" /></p>\r\n<p>For nearly 60 years, sternwheelers provided a transportation lifeline to the many isolated communities on Kootenay Lake. The SS Moyie and her sister ships literally opened the Kootenay region to miners, businesses, farmers and pioneer families. When she was launched on October 22, 1898, there were no roads, no trains, and of course no air travel into these hidden mountain valleys. The ships were the only means of mass transportation, freight and mail service. And so they came  the rich, the poor, prospectors and settlers  sailing up the pristine waterways on ships that were themselves works of art. The sternwheelers were the bearers of our destiny.</p><p>When she was finally dry docked in 1957 the Village of Kaslo purchased her from the CPR for the grand sum of $1.00. Breathing life into her history has involved thousands of hours of labour, research and the skills of a generation of workers. Storyboards at street level describe the scope and scale of the renovations that are still ongoing today. The latest renovation project has been to restore a caboose to the 1940s time period. To date the exterior has been completed and a photo gallery depicting transportation on the lake has been installed inside. This fascinating collection of photos and models will be on display for only one more year. After that time, the interior of the caboose will be restored to reflect its original purpose.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now a designated National Historic Site and BC Landmark, the sternwheeler is open daily for guided or self-guided tours from Mothers Day through to Thanksgiving weekend.</p><p>The Moyie is located at 324 Front Street.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.klhs.bc.ca/\" style=\"text-decoration: none; color: rgb(138, 96, 191);\">For more information www.klhs.bc.ca</a>or phone/fax 250-353-2525, or write a letter to Box 537, Kaslo, BC V0G 1M0.</p><a href=\"http://www.klhs.bc.ca/\" style=\"text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(138, 96, 191); background-color: rgb(255, 253, 230);\"><img width=\"500\" height=\"\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/moyie.jpg\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 1pt; border-bottom: 1pt solid rgb(0, 0, 255); padding: 10px; display: block; text-decoration: none; clear: both; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" class=\"clear-all-center\" alt=\"moyie\" /></a><p>&nbsp;</p></div></div>','<div>\r\n<div align=\"center\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; -x-system-font: none;\" id=\"indexheader\">\r\n\r\n<div align=\"center\">\r\n<img height=\"99\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/moyie.gif\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" alt=\"The History of the People of Kaslo\" />\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r','','1262737393','2');
INSERT INTO `drupal_node_revisions` VALUES ('13','13','1','Lifestyle','<div id=\"indexheader\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;\"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"100\" alt=\"Lifestyle\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/lifestyle.gif\" /></div></div><div id=\"content\" style=\"clear: both; display: block; top: 50px; left: 0px; width: 500px; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 14px; line-height: 15px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p class=\"intro\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: larger;\"><strong>Big Mountains&hellip; small village&hellip; friendly people<br />and a lifestyle that lets you enjoy all three&hellip;</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align: left;\">For people from larger centres used to anonymity as they walk their downtown streets, the friendliness of the Kaslovians can take them by surprise. Whether you are a visitor or a local, passersby are likely to smile and say hello. Couple that with the Victorian architecture and the old western false fronts on the main drag and you can be forgiven for thinking that you\'ve stepped into the pages of a storybook from the past. The cell phones, the internet cafe and cappuccino shops are what will make you realize you\'re still very much in the present.</p></td></tr><tr><td><div align=\"center\"><img width=\"490\" alt=\"Kaslo\'s May Day Celebration.\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; display: block; padding-top: 4px; padding-bottom: 8px; border-left-color: black;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/lifestyle1.jpg\" /></div></td></tr><tr><td><p>The May Day celebrations held each year on Queen Victoria\'s birthday, are a testimony to this village lifestyle. For over 100 years the children have performed the ancient and intricate Maypole dance. Grandparents watch and remember the day when as children they danced with the ribbons in their hands.</p><p>There is much to smile about here&hellip;</p></td></tr><tr><td><div align=\"center\"><img width=\"490\" alt=\"Kaslo\'s May Day Participants.\" style=\"border-width: 0px 0px 0px thin; display: block; padding-top: 4px; padding-bottom: 8px; border-left-color: black;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/lifestyle2.jpg\" /></div></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p></div><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','<div id=\"indexheader\" style=\"width: 500px; text-align: center; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: bolder; font-size: 24px; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;\"><div align=\"center\"><img height=\"100\" alt=\"Lifestyle\" style=\"border-width: 0px; display: block;\" src=\"http://www.kaslovisitorguide.com/pics/lifestyle.gif\" /></div></div><div id=\"content\" style=\"clear: both; display: block; top: 50px; left: 0px; width: 500px; font-family: \'Lucida Grand\',Arial,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal','','1262737545','2');
